English

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

Borrowed from German Fischer (“fisherman”).

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • Rhymes: -ɪʃə(ɹ)

Proper noun

[edit]

Fischer (plural Fischers)

  1. A surname from German [in turn originating as an occupation].
    • 2008 March 2, Bruce Barcott, “The Higher They Climb”, in The New York Times‎[1]:
      An athletic kid from New Jersey, Fischer was known as a bold risk taker — they called him “the fallingest man in climbing” — until an old-school cragger taught him the Zen of controlled ascent.

Derived terms

[edit]
  • Fischer esterification
  • Fischerian
  • Fischer indole synthesis
  • Fischer projection
  • Fischer random chess
  • Fischer-Tropsch process
  • Karl Fischer reagent
  • Karl Fischer titration

Statistics

[edit]
  • According to the 2010 United States Census, Fischer is the 455th most common surname in the United States, belonging to 72,357 individuals. Fischer is most common among White (94.3%) individuals.

German

[edit]
German Wikipedia has an article on:
Fischer
Wikipedia de

Etymology

[edit]

From Middle High German vischære, vischer, from Old High German fiscari, from Proto-Germanic *fiskārijaz.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /ˈfɪʃɐ/
  • Audio:(file)
  • Audio (Germany (Berlin)):(file)
  • Rhymes: -ɪʃɐ
  • Hyphenation: Fi‧scher

Noun

[edit]

Fischer m (strong, genitive Fischers, plural Fischer, feminine Fischerin)

  1. agent noun of fischen
  2. fisher, fisherman (male or of unspecified gender)
  3. component part in various compound nouns, e.g. Amazonasfischer (“Amazon kingfisher”), Austernfischer (“oystercatcher”)
  4. component part in various compounds for different kinds of fishing boats, e.g. Grundschleppnetzfischer (“trawler”)
